"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |<ref name=\":35\" group=\"note\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | April 15\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |530\n| 370\n| 1508\n| 21\n| 3894\n| 160\n| 1885\n| 239\n| 6681\n| 3122\n| 2308\n| 6279\n| 2350\n| 572\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |18\n| 23\n| 56\n|\n| 140\n| 25\n| 154\n| 5\n| 221\n| 147\n| 95\n| 113\n| 100\n| 11\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |<ref name=\":44\" group=\"note\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | April 16\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |550\n| 382\n| 1605\n| 21\n| 4245\n| 170\n| 1985\n| 248\n| 7206\n| 3342\n| 2466\n| 6820\n| 2503\n| 638\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |18\n| 26\n| 63\n|\n| 159\n| 25\n| 164\n| 5\n| 258\n| 173\n| 99\n| 132\n| 110\n| 13\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |<ref name=\":45\" group=\"note\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | April 17\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |573\n| 383\n| 1659\n| 21\n| 4584\n| 173\n| 2134\n| 258\n| 7744\n| 3499\n| 2577\n| 7272\n| 2765\n| 760\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |20\n| 26\n| 75\n|\n| 178\n| 25\n| 184\n| 6\n| 294\n| 195\n| 111\n| 132\n| 118\n| 40\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |<ref name=\":46\" group=\"note\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | April 18\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |590\n| 385\n| 1698\n| 23\n| 4914\n| 177\n| 2254\n| 306\n| 8297\n| 3659\n| 2688\n| 7696\n| 2952\n| 733\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |20\n| 27\n| 83\n|\n| 193\n| 25\n| 203\n| 6\n| 334\n| 215\n| 128\n| 156\n| 129\n| 41\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |<ref name=\":47\" group=\"note\"/>\n|-\n ! style=\"border-right: 2px solid #888;\" | Date\n ! {{vert header|Barnstable}}\n ! {{vert header|Berkshire}}\n ! {{vert header|Bristol}}\n ! {{vert header|Dukes and Nantucket}}\n ! {{vert header|Essex}}\n ! {{vert header|Franklin}}\n ! {{vert header|Hampden}}\n ! {{vert header|Hampshire}}\n ! {{vert header|Middlesex}}\n ! {{vert header|Norfolk}}\n ! {{vert header|Plymouth}}\n ! {{vert header|Suffolk}}\n ! {{vert header|Worcester}}\n ! {{vert header|Unknown}}\n ! {{vert header|Barnstable| cellstyle=border-left: 2px solid #888;}}\n ! {{vert header|Berkshire}}\n ! {{vert header|Bristol}}\n ! {{vert header|Dukes and Nantucket}}\n ! {{vert header|Essex}}\n ! {{vert header|Franklin}}\n ! {{vert header|Hampden}}\n ! {{vert header|Hampshire}}\n ! {{vert header|Middlesex}}\n ! {{vert header|Norfolk}}\n ! {{vert header|Plymouth}}\n ! {{vert header|Suffolk}}\n ! {{vert header|Worcester}}\n ! {{vert header|Unknown}}\n ! style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |Source\n|-\n| style=\"border-right: 2px solid #888;\" | <strong>County <br/> pop <br/> (2020)</strong>\n| {{vert header|213,413}}\n| {{vert header|126,348}}\n| {{vert header|564,022}}\n| {{vert header|28,679}}\n| {{vert header|790,638}}\n| {{vert header|70,963}}\n| {{vert header|470,406}}\n| {{vert header|161,355}}\n| {{vert header|1,614,714}}\n| {{vert header|705,388}}\n| {{vert header|518,132}}\n| {{vert header|807,252}}\n| {{vert header|830,839}}\n| style=\"border-right: 2px solid #888;\"|\n| {{vert header|213,413}}\n| {{vert header|126,348}}\n| {{vert header|564,022}}\n| {{vert header|28,679}}\n| {{vert header|790,638}}\n| {{vert header|70,963}}\n| {{vert header|470,406}}\n| {{vert header|161,355}}\n| {{vert header|1,614,714}}\n| {{vert header|705,388}}\n| {{vert header|518,132}}\n| {{vert header|807,252}}\n| {{vert header|830,839}}\n|\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.massachusetts-demographics.com/counties_by_population |access-date = April 6, 2020 | title = Massachusetts Counties by Population | website= Massachusetts Demographics}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Government response ==\n[[File:ASM show at BCEC.agr.jpg|thumb|Interior of the [[Boston Convention and Exhibition Center]] (BCEC), pictured during a 2016 conference. The BCEC will be converted to a [[field hospital]].]]\n\nCiting the rapid increase in cases, Governor Charlie Baker declared a [[state of emergency]] for Massachusetts on March 10.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/governor-charlie-baker-declares-state-of-emergency-coronavirus-3-10-2020/31356404 | title = Gov. Baker declares state of emergency as Mass. coronavirus cases more than double | date = March 10, 2020 | publisher = WCVB | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Locke | first = Kaitlyn | url = https://www.wgbh.org/news/local-news/2020/03/10/baker-declares-state-of-emergency-92-total-coronavirus-cases-in-massachusetts | title = Baker Declares State Of Emergency; 92 Total Coronavirus Cases in Massachusetts | date = March 10, 2020 | publisher = WGBH News | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> During a press conference on March 14, 2020, Governor Baker established an emergency command center and promised to expand statewide lab testing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/14/metro/baker-sets-up-virus-command-center/|title=State figures on testing raise questions about efforts to contain outbreak |website=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Governor Baker banned all public gatherings of over 25 people, closed all K\u201312 public schools from March 17 through April 7, and banned on-site service at bars and restaurants for the same period.<ref>{{cite news | title = Gov. Baker bans gatherings of over 25 people, orders school closure, restaurants take-out only | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/gov-charlie-baker-massachusetts-covid-19-coronavirus-update-march-15-2020/31647097 | access-date = March 17, 2020 | publisher = WCVB | date = March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 25, Governor Baker ordered all schools and childcare services to be closed through May 4, extending the original closure by three weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/news/baker-polito-administration-announces-extension-of-school-and-non-emergency-child-care-program|title=Baker-Polito Administration Announces Extension of School and Non-Emergency Child Care Program Closures and Steps to Ensure Housing Stability To Support COVID-19 Response|author= Office of Governor Charlie Baker and Lt. Governor Karyn Polito|publisher=Mass.gov|date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Governor Baker announced a stay-at-home advisory to be effective from March 24 until April 7. On March 31 the advisory which was extended to May 4.<ref name=\"Feuer\"/> Starting March 31, hotels, motels and online rentals like [[Airbnb]] were ordered to close to recreational travelers so they could be used to house essential workers and displaced residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/news/baker-polito-administration-extends-non-essential-business-closures-and-executive-branch|title=Baker-Polito Administration Extends Non-Essential Business Closures and Executive Branch Employee Guidance|publisher=Mass.gov}}</ref> The [[Boston Convention and Exhibition Center]] is being prepared as a 1,000-bed [[field hospital]] for COVID-19 patients, including 500 beds for infected homeless patients.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/04/02/1000-beds-planned-for-boston-convention-center-to-treat-coronavirus-patients|title=1,000 Beds Planned For Boston Convention Center To Treat Coronavirus Patients|date=April 2, 2020|first=Ally|last=Jarmanning|work=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> The [[DCU Center]] in Worcester was set up as a field hospital for recovering COVID-19 patients, overseen by [[UMass Memorial Medical Center]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/03/31/dcu-arena-covid-19-field-hospital|title=Worcester's DCU Center Will Become 250-Bed Field Hospital For Stable COVID-19 Patients|publisher=www.wbur.org}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, Governor Baker asked travelers from out of state to avoid Massachusetts or to self-quarantine upon arrival for 14 days. Electronic highway signs were activated, and travelers arriving at [[Logan International Airport]], [[Worcester Regional Airport]], and [[South Station]] were given flyers.<ref name=\"WBUR-Baker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2020/03/27/baker-out-of-state-quarantine|title=Baker Asks Visitors To Self-Isolate For Two Weeks \u2014 Or Not Come At All|publisher=www.wbur.org}}</ref> Medical students were graduated early, and emergency orders were issued giving some nurses with more than two years of experience authority to write prescriptions, and granting incoming medical residents and interns 90-day medical licenses.<ref name=\"WBUR-Baker\"/>\n\nThe [[Massachusetts Registry of Motor Vehicles]] moved to an appointment-only system to avoid overcrowding, and the state extended deadlines for many renewals by 60 days to reduce the need for in-person transactions. With visits down about 90%, eight of the 30 RMV branches closed completely. The National Association of Government Employees, representing customer service employees at the RMV, asked that the remaining offices be closed for worker safety, but the Secretary of Transportation said essential workers needed the RMV to continue operating.<ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/10/metro/rmv-workers-union-calls-agency-shutter-all-branches/ RMV workers union calls for agency to shutter all branches]</ref>\n\nWhen people in parks were found to not be following social distancing, many parks and playgrounds were closed. Some cities removed or blocked off basketball hoops and other amenities to discourage people from gathering. <ref>https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2020/03/29/marty-walsh-boston-parks-coronavirus</ref> Beaches and their parking lots were also ordered to close.<ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/02/metro/parking-lots-state-beaches-are-closing/</ref> On April 5, Boston's Mayor Walsh issued a stay-at-home advisory for the city of Boston. All non-essential workers were asked to stay home from 9:00{{Nbsp}}p.m. to 6:00{{Nbsp}}a.m., starting April 6. People were encouraged to wear masks when outside the home, but instructed to leave medical masks for essential workers and make their own if necessary. All baseball, tennis, and hockey fields in parks were ordered to be closed. Residents were instructed not to visit family or fields outside of their households. The restrictions are enforceable by fines.<ref name=\"WGBH-Curfew\"/>\n\n== Spread among population groups ==\n=== Long-term care facilities ===\n{{As of|2020|04|19|df=US}}, 884 deaths have been attributed to COVID-19 in [[Nursing home care|long-term care facilities]] in Massachusetts. 6,121 residents and employees at these facilities have tested positive for SARS-CoV-19, and 254 long-term care facilities in Massachusetts have reported at least one case of COVID-19.<ref name=\"MDPH-Cases\"/> The state has allocated $130{{Nbsp}}million in additional funding to these facilities, and has offered signing bonuses to job applicants in an attempt to increase staffing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/04/15/nursing-homes-assisted-living-baker-state-plans-efforts|title=As Deaths Rise At Nursing Homes, Updates On Mass.' COVID-19 Plans For Long-Term Care Facilities|last=Creamer|first=Lisa|last2=Moran|first2=Barbara|date=April 15, 2020|website=[[WBUR]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> \n\n==== Soldiers' Home in Holyoke ====\nOn March 30, a potential cluster of COVID-19 cases was reported in [[Holyoke, Massachusetts]] at [[Soldiers' Home in Holyoke|Soldiers' Home]], a nursing facility for military veterans. Eleven residents had recently died, and another eleven residents along with several staff members had tested positive for SARS-CoV-19.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lisinski |first=Chris |url=https://www.wwlp.com/news/local-news/hampden-county/holyoke-soldiers-home-superintendent-placed-on-leave-effective-immediately/ |title=11 veterans dead, several residents, staff exposed to COVID-19 at Holyoke Soldiers' Home |publisher=WWLP |date= |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> Holyoke Mayor [[Alex Morse]] accused the nursing facility of mismanagement and lack of transparency in the events surrounding the outbreak and its resulting fatalities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/03/coronavirus-at-holyoke-soldiers-home-alex-morse-says-lack-of-urgency-and-mismangement-at-facility-where-as-many-as-12-have-died.html|title=Coronavirus at Holyoke Soldiers' Home: Alex Morse says mismanagement at facility where as many as 12 have died|date=March 31, 2020|website=masslive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.masslive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-at-holyoke-soldiers-home-family-members-say-they-were-left-in-the-dark-as-sickness-spread.html|title=Family members say they were left in the dark as COVID-19 spread at Holyoke Soldiers Home|date=March 31, 2020|website=masslive}}</ref> Governor Baker announced on April 1 that he had appointed an independent investigator to examine the outbreak at Soldiers' Home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.masslive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/coronavirus-gov-charlie-baker-appoints-independent-investigator-to-examine-holyoke-soldiers-home-in-wake-of-covid-19-deaths.html|title=Coronavirus: Gov. Charlie Baker appoints independent investigator to examine Holyoke Soldiers' Home in wake of COVID-19 deaths|date=April 1, 2020|website=masslive}}</ref> On April 2, three more residents of Holyoke Soldiers' Home died, bringing that outbreak's total number of deaths to 18.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwlp.com/news/local-news/hampden-county/18-veterans-now-confirmed-dead-at-soldiers-home-in-holyoke/|title=18 veterans now confirmed dead at Soldiers' Home in Holyoke|date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> On April 3, [[Holyoke Medical Center]] announced that a total of 21 residents of the Soldier's Home in Holyoke had died, at least 15 of whom tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mike Saccone |url=https://twitter.com/mikesacconetv/status/1246140619883413509 |title=BREAKING: 21 veteran residents at the Holyoke Soldiers' Home have died. 15 had tested positive for coroanvirus. 59 veterans at the home have tested positive for coronavirus & 160 have tested negative. #Boston |publisher=Twitter.com |date=April 12, 2009 |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> According to officials, a total of 59 residents had tested positive for SARS-CoV-2.<ref>{{cite web|last=Markos |first=Mary |url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2020/04/03/21-veterans-die-at-holyoke-soldiers-home-15-confirmed-for-coronavirus/ |title=21 veterans die at Holyoke Soldiers' Home, 15 confirmed for coronavirus |work=[[Boston Herald]] |date=March 31, 2020 |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/03/nation/years-understaffing-mismanagement-set-deadly-stage-coronavirus-outbreak-holyoke-soldiers-home-employees-say/ |title=Years of understaffing, mismanagement set deadly stage for coronavirus outbreak at Holyoke Soldiers' Home, employees say |website=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> On April 10, the [[United States Attorney|U.S. Attorney's office]] in Boston announced that it would be opening a federal investigation into whether Soldiers' Home violated the rights of its patients by failing to provide them adequate medical care and protection during the COVID-19 outbreak.<REF>https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/10/us/holyoke-soldiers-home-us-attorney-investigation/index.html</ref> {{As of|2020|04|17|alt=As of April 17}}, 92 residents have tested positive for SARS-CoV-2 at the facility and 56 residents have died. Of the 56 people who died, 47 tested positive for the virus and seven tested negative. One test is pending and one test result is unknown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwlp.com/news/local-news/hampden-county/veteran-deaths-at-soldiers-home-in-holyoke-at-56-47-had-covid-19-over-90-still-positive/|title=Veteran deaths at Soldiers' Home in Holyoke at 56; 47 had COVID-19, over 90 still positive|last=Asiamah|first=Nancy|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[WWLP]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Life Care Center of Nashoba Valley ====\n[[File:A medic with the Massachusetts National Guard takes a nasal swab that will be used to test for COVID-19 with a resident of the Life Care Center of Nashoba Valley Littleton Mass. April 3 2020.jpg|thumb|A medic with the [[Massachusetts National Guard]] and a resident of the [[Life_Care_Centers_of_America#Littleton,_Massachusetts_COVID-19_Outbreak|Life Care Center]] of [[Nashoba Valley]] [[nursing home]] handle a nasal swab that will be used to test for [[COVID-19]]]]\nThe [[Life Care Centers of America|Life Care Center]] of [[Nashoba Valley]] in [[Littleton, Massachusetts|Littleton]] reported on April 10 that 75 of its 204 employees were out sick and that at least 14 of them had tested positive for SARS-CoV-2.<ref>Life Care Center of Nashoba Valley in Littleton, where 10 residents with the virus have died, its parent company said Friday that 75 of its 204 employees were out sick and that 14 have been infected with COVID-19.</ref> On April 11, officials at the Life Care Center of Nashoba Valley announced that Maria Krier, a nurse who had spoken out about improper training at the nursing home, had died. She had told reporters that she believed management had no experience with infectious disease and that that had contributed to the spread of COVID-19 at the facility.<ref>https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/whistleblower-nurse-who-spoke-out-about-littleton-nursing-home-dies-of-covid-19/ar-BB12uxHD</ref> On April 15, a letter was found outside the Life Care Center that made threatening and violent remarks, referencing the COVID-19 outbreak. {{As of|2020|04|13|alt=As of April 13}}, fourteen residents of the facility had died in the period since March 27. 67 residents tested positive for SARS-CoV-19 among the 98 who have been tested for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/04/18/coronavirus-threatening-letter-found-life-care-center-of-nashoba-valley-littleton-police/|title=Threatening Letter Found At Life Care Center Of Nashoba Valley|last=|first=|date=April 18, 2020|website=CBS Boston|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Other facilities ====\nOn April 3, AdviniaCare in [[Wilmington, Massachusetts]] announced that 51 of 98 residents had tested positive for the virus. AdviniaCare had been selected to become a recovery center for Boston-area COVID-19 patients who were still contagious but had recovered sufficiently to be discharged out of the intensive care units of Boston area hospitals. However, after the high number of residents tested positive for SARS-CoV-19, AdviniaCare announced they would be delaying the plan to relocate residents and convert the facility into a recovery center.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/03/metro/51-residents-positive-coronavirus-wilmington-nursing-home-despite-having-no-symptoms/|title=51 residents positive for coronavirus at Wilmington nursing home, despite having no symptoms|date=April 3, 2020|website=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> {{As of|2020|04|17|alt=As of April 17}}, 25 patients at the facility had died from COVID-19. 55 residents had been infected and 45 had recovered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/17/nation/covid-19-claims-25-patients-wilmington-facility-initially-slated-become-recovery-site/|title=Coronavirus claims 25 patients at Wilmington facility initially slated to become recovery site - The Boston Globe|last=Crimaldi|first=Laura|last2=Krantz|first2=Laura|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The Boston Globe]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> \n\n{{As of|2020|04|04|alt=As of April 4,}} 21 residents of the Charlwell House Health and Rehabilitation Center in [[Norwood, Massachusetts]] had died in less than two weeks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/04/metro/residents-families-angry-helpless-coronavirus-overwhelms-nursing-homes/|title=Residents and families angry and helpless as coronavirus overwhelms nursing homes|last=Weisman|first=Robert|last2=Krantz|first2=Laura|date=April 4, 2020|website=[[The Boston Globe]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> {{As of|2020|04|03|alt=As of April 3}}, seven of the people who died had tested positive for SARS-CoV-19, and only twenty of the more than 200 residents and staff at the facility had been able to be tested for SARS-CoV-2.<ref>{{cite web|last=Szaniszlo |first=Marie |url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2020/04/03/deaths-at-nursing-homes-in-norwood-littleton-linked-to-coronavirus/ |title=Seven people who died at Norwood nursing home tested positive for COVID-19 |work=[[Boston Herald]] |date=March 19, 2020 |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2020|04|10|df=US|alt=As of April 10}}, eight deaths have been reported at Jack Satter House in [[Revere, Massachusetts|Revere]], a nursing home run by Hebrew Senior Life.<ref>{{cite news |title=Boston-area senior housing community with Jewish ties reports 6 coronavirus deaths |url=https://www.jta.org/quick-reads/boston-area-senior-housing-community-under-jewish-auspices-reports-6-coronavirus-deaths |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=Jewish Telegraphic Agency}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus cases at senior centers and nursing homes in Massachusetts are rising: 'It's a hot zone' |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/01/nation/covid-deaths-senior-centers-nursing-homes-rise/ |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hebrewseniorlife.org/about-us/covid-19-coronavirus-guidance/jack-satter-house-covid-19-update|title=Jack Satter House - COVID-19 Update|last=|first=|date=|website=Hebrew Senior Life|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 12, officials with JGS Lifecare in [[Longmeadow, Massachusetts]] announced in a letter to benefactors that 21 residents of the facility had died of COVID-19 and that 93 residents and 43 staff had tested positive.<ref>https://www.bostonherald.com/2020/04/12/coronavirus-in-massachusetts-21-residents-of-nursing-home-die-93-test-positive/</ref><ref>https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/04/11/21-residents-dead-jgs-lifecare-senior-home</ref> This number had more than tripled since the facility had reported 29 cases on April 2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwlp.com/news/local-news/hampden-county/jgs-lifecare-covid-19-cases-more-than-triple-in-10-days-totaling-93/|title=JGS Lifecare COVID-19 cases more than triple in 10 days totaling 93|last=Kincade|first=Katrina|date=April 11, 2020|website=[[WWLP]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2020|04|16|alt=As of April 16}}, 17 residents of the Belmont Manor Nursing Rehabilitation Center had died in a five-day period, bringing the overall total of deaths at the facility to 30.<ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/16/nation/27-residents-belmont-manor-nursing-home-have-now-died-covid-19-owner-says-up-13-reported-deaths/</ref>\n\nOn April 17, officials from the Alliance Health at West Acres nursing home in Brockton, Massachusetts announced that a total of 37 residents had tested positive for COVID-19 and 15 others had died from the virus.<ref name=enterprisenews>https://www.enterprisenews.com/news/20200417/39-test-positive-for-coronavirus-15-have-died-at-west-acres-in-brockton</ref> The City of Brockton also announced that at least 29 of the city's 46 deaths attributed to COVID-19 were from residents of the long-term care facilities within the city. These deaths also included ten residents of the Brockton Health Center who died after contracting the disease, and at least four residents at Saint Joseph Manor Nursing facility.<ref name=enterprisenews/>\n\n=== Racial disparities ===\nPreliminary data has shown that African Americans and others of African descent in Massachusetts have been disproportionately impacted by COVID-19. Although only 25% of the population of Boston are black, they have accounted for 41% of the COVID-19 cases in the city. On April 9, the city of Boston announced it had created a COVID-19 Health Inequities Task Force, which would advise the city in addressing inequality among testing, data analysis, and healthcare for underrepresented racial groups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/04/16/covid-19-coronavirus-african-american-boston-black|title=COVID-19 Hits Boston's Black Community Especially Hard|last=Oakes|first=Bob|last2=Fleming|first2=Wilder|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[WBUR]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> At Massachusetts General Hospital, the proportion of Latinos among COVID-19 patients is four times the percentage usually being treated at the hospital. Public health experts have reported that the virus has disproportionately affected Massachusetts communities with high black, latino, and immigrant populations because many in those communities are exposed to the virus through essential jobs at grocery stores, public transit, and food delivery services. They also attribute the higher prevalence of the disease to members of those communities living in smaller or more densely populated homes, making social distancing a challenge.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/07/nation/coronavirus-may-be-hitting-hard-black-latino-communities/|title=Coronavirus may be hitting harder in Black and Latino communities|last=Ryan|first=Andrew|last2=Lazar|first2=Kay|date=April 7, 2020|website=[[The Boston Globe]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2020|04|07|alt=As of April 7}}, the Massachusetts Department of Public Health, the primary organization compiling test data in Massachusetts, has declined to release data on the specific impact of COVID-19 to racial and ethnic groups.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Prison population ===\nOn March 21, the [[Massachusetts Department of Correction]] (DOC) announced the first confirmed case of COVID-19 among its inmate population. According to officials at the [[Massachusetts Treatment Center]] (MTC) in Bridgewater, Massachusetts, a male inmate who is serving a life sentence tested positive. Massachusetts DOC noted at the time that this was the only known case of COVID-19 in its inmate population.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wcvb.com/article/inmate-at-bridgewater-prison-massachusetts-treatment-center-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-officials-say/31846456|title=Inmate at local prison tests positive for coronavirus, officials say|date=March 21, 2020|website=WCVB|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> As of April 15, four prisoners at the Massachusetts Treatment Center have died from COVID-19, making it the only prison in the state that has reported inmate deaths from the virus.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2020/04/15/jails-prisons-latest-coronavirus-cases-mtc|title=More Than 150 Positive COVID-19 Cases Reported Among Prisoners, Staff Inside Mass. Jails And Prisons|last=Becker|first=Deborah|date=April 15, 2020|website=[[WBUR]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 10, the Massachusetts DOC released data showing the rate of infection among female inmates at [[Massachusetts Correctional Institution \u2013 Framingham]] (MCI \u2013 Framingham) was nearly ten times that of the overall state prison population, with 17 prisoners, or 7.8 percent of the facility's population, infected.<ref>https://commonwealthmagazine.org/criminal-justice/coronavirus-infection-in-state-prisons-more-than-two-times-statewide-rate/</ref>\n\nAs of April 15, more than 150 cases of COVID-19 have been confirmed among inmates and staff members in Massachusetts jails and prisons.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Homeless population ===\nOn April 7, the Chief of Boston Health and Human Services Marty Martinez spoke at Boston Mayor Walsh's press conference, where he reported that there were around 200 cases of COVID-19 among homeless people in Boston, which was around 30% of the homeless people who had been tested. The city of Boston allocated 500 of the beds at the field hospital being created at the Boston Convention and Exposition Center to go to homeless people with COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wgbh.org/news/local-news/2020/04/07/one-in-three-among-boston-homeless-have-tested-positive-for-coronavirus-city-officials-say|title=One In Three Among Boston Homeless Have Tested Positive For Coronavirus, City Officials Say|last=Thompson|first=Isaiah|date=April 7, 2020|website=[[WGBH]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> A homeless shelter in Worcester found on April 17 that out of 114 shelter guests who were tested for SARS-CoV-19, 49 (43%) tested positive. Many of those who tested positive were asymptomatic or had mild symptoms; Dr. Erik Garcia, the medical director of the Homeless Outreach and Advocacy Project at the Family Health Center of Worcester, said that \"There were some symptoms, but certainly none of the classic symptoms... And most people were complaining of a slight worsening of the chronic cough that they already had \u2014 no fevers and no other symptoms.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2020/04/17/worcester-homeless-population-covid-19-coronavirus|title=Testing At Worcester Homeless Shelter Finds 43% Positive For Coronavirus|last=Jolicoeur|first=Lynn|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[WBUR]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> After a cluster of coronavirus cases were traced back to the Boston Pine Street Inn shelter, the Boston Health Care for the Homeless Program tested all shelter guests for the virus and found that out of 397 people tested, 146 tested positive but had been experiencing no symptoms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.masslive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/coronavirus-spread-testing-shows-stunning-asymptomatic-covid-19-rate-at-boston-homeless-shelter.html|title='Stunning' asymptomatic COVID-19 tests among Boston homeless|last=Karalis|first=John|date=April 15, 2020|website=[[MassLive]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> The state of Massachusetts has created isolation sites in [[Pittsfield, Massachusetts|Pittsfield]], [[Taunton, Massachusetts|Taunton]], and [[Lexington, Massachusetts|Lexington]] for people who are homeless and who have tested positive for SARS-CoV-19 or have a doctor's note recommending they isolate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/info-details/homeless-covid-19-isolation-sites|title=Homeless COVID-19 Isolation Sites|last=|first=|date=|website=Government of Massachusetts|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Societal effects ==\nThe sudden surge of cases in Massachusetts during the week of March 9 led many organizations to ask employees to work from home, and prompted museums and libraries to close. This led to a noticeable decline in Boston's rush hour traffic; in some cases, drive times for major highways dropped by 30 to 50 percent.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2020/03/11/boston-traffic-coronavirus | title = Coronavirus: Here's how much Boston's rush hour traffic has dropped &#124; Boston.com | website = Boston.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Grocery stores ===\n[[Panic buying]], especially since the week of March 11, led to shortages of some products, and there were crowds and long lines at grocery stores as early in the day as 7:00{{Nbsp}}a.m.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/13/nation/store-shelves-picked-clean-people-panic-buy-goods-local-supermarkets/ | title = Store shelves picked clean as people panic-buy goods at local supermarkets |newspaper= [[The Boston Globe]] | access-date = April 6, 2020 | date= March 13, 2020 | first= Steve |last=Annear |first2=Janelle |last2=Nanos}}</ref> Some grocery retailers such as [[Stop & Shop]] adjusted their hours to allow employees more time to restock and to offer older and more vulnerable people a time where they can shop separately.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/03/16/coronavirus-stop-and-shop-senior-hours/ |title=Stop & Shop Creates Hours Only For Customers 60 And Older During Coronavirus Pandemic |date=March 16, 2020 |website=CBS Boston}}</ref> Later, grocery stores implemented stricter measures, including limiting the amount of people allowed inside stores at a time, and marking queues to maintain social distancing. <ref>https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/04/01/coronavirus-market-basket-social-distance/</ref> \n\n=== Schools and universities ===\nSchool closures began in early March, when Massachusetts Institute of Technology announced on March 9 that it was moving to only-online classes for the remainder of the spring semester.<ref name=\"MIT-Update\">{{cite web|url=http://web.mit.edu/covid19/update-to-undergraduates/|title=Update to Undergraduate Students|date=March 9, 2020|website=[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 9, two elementary schools in the [[Plainville, Massachusetts|Plainville]] school district and one in [[Arlington, Massachusetts|Arlington]] were closed for the day due to COVID-19 tests being conducted on two parents and one child.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Cuoco | first = John | url = https://whdh.com/news/multiple-massachusetts-schools-closed-monday-as-coronavirus-cases-continue-to-rise/ | title = Multiple Massachusetts schools closed Monday as coronavirus cases continue to rise | date = March 9, 2020 | work = WHDH 7News | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> [[Northeastern University]], which had already closed satellite campuses in San Francisco and Seattle, hesitated to close their main campus for fear of international students losing their [[F visa]] status. On March 6 the university publicly called on the [[Department of Homeland Security]] to grant clemency for international students so the university could close.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://news.northeastern.edu/coronavirus/university-messages/president-aouns-letter-to-the-u-s-department-of-homeland-security-on-f-1-student-visas/ | title = President Aoun's letter to the U.S. Department of Homeland Security on F-1 student visas | last = Aoun | first = Joseph E. | date = March 6, 2020 | website = Northeastern University}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, [[Harvard University]] announced that its classes would be online-only for the rest of the spring semester.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2020/3/11/harvard-coronavirus-classes-cancelled/ | title = Harvard Moves Classes Online, Asks Students Not to Return After Spring Break in Response to Coronavirus | date = March 11, 2020 | work = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Carraggi | first = Mike | url = https://patch.com/massachusetts/boston/harvard-asks-students-not-return-break-amid-virus-fears | title = Harvard, Others Ask Students Not To Return From Break, Go Virtual | date = March 10, 2020 | work = Boston, MA Patch | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://web.mit.edu/covid19/update-from-president-l-rafael-reif-to-the-mit-community/ | title = Update from President L. Rafael Reif to the MIT Community | last = Reif | first = L. Rafael | date = March 10, 2020 | website = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200311023015/https://web.mit.edu/covid19/update-from-president-l-rafael-reif-to-the-mit-community/ | archive-date = March 11, 2020 | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> The University of Massachusetts Boston informed faculty that they should prepare to teach remotely.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Aliyu | first = Wale | url = https://www.boston25news.com/news/umass-boston-preparing-roll-out-online-classes-coronavirus-concerns-grow/76QRLNDDDRB2VGXAKLFU3OPNCU/ | title = UMass Boston preparing to roll out online classes as coronavirus concerns grow | date = March 10, 2020 | work = Boston 25 News | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> [[Amherst College]], located in [[Western Massachusetts]], instructed students on spring break to not return to campus, and moved all classes online for the remainder of the semester.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/coronavirus-prompts-amherst-college-to-move-to-remote-learning-for-rest-of-semester/31307851 | title = Coronavirus prompts Amherst College to move to remote learning for rest of semester | date = March 10, 2020 | work = WCVB | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> [[Emerson College]], [[Tufts University]], [[Babson College]], [[Smith College]], and [[Wheaton College (Massachusetts)|Wheaton College]] all canceled in-person classes and moved classes online.<ref name=\"Corrado\">{{Cite news | last = Corrado | first = Kerri | url = https://whdh.com/news/which-mass-colleges-are-making-changes-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ | title = Which Mass. colleges are making changes amid coronavirus outbreak? | date = March 11, 2020 | work = WHDH 7News | access-date = March 11, 2020 | last2 = Connolly | first2 = Brynne}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, several schools were closed including Hopkinton Public Schools, Loker Elementary and [[Wayland Middle School]], and Clark Avenue Middle School.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Cho | first = Diane | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/coronavirus/coronavirus-concerns-shut-down-hopkinton-wayland-schools-wednesday/2089034/ | title = Multiple Mass. Schools Closed Wednesday Over Coronavirus Outbreak | date = March 11, 2020 | work = NBC Boston | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> Northeastern University and [[Boston University]] moved all classes online.<ref name=\"Corrado\"/><ref>{{cite web | url = https://news.northeastern.edu/coronavirus/university-messages/advancing-our-mission-in-a-time-of-uncertainty/ | title = Advancing our Mission in a Time of Uncertainty | last = Aoun | first = Joseph E. | website = Northeastern University | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bu.edu/articles/2020/bu-all-classes-online-coronavirus/ | title = Updated: BU Moves All Classes Online Due to Coronavirus \u2014 Questions and Answers | last = Most | first = Doug | date = March 11, 2020 | website = BU Today | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 14, Northeastern University informed students they would need to vacate their dormitories by 5:00&nbsp;p.m. on March 17.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/03/15/coronavirus-northeastern-university-student-tests-positive/ | title = Northeastern University Student Tests Positive For Coronavirus | date = March 15, 2020 | website = CBS Boston | access-date = March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/03/14/coronavirus-northeastern-unversitity-students-must-leave-dorms-by-tuesday/ | title = Northeastern Reverses Decision, Says Students Must Leave Dorms For Coronavirus Prevention | date = March 14, 2020 | first = Jim | last = Smith | publisher = CBS Boston}}</ref> Up to this point students were taking online classes but allowed to remain on university property.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://news.northeastern.edu/2020/03/14/northeastern-requests-that-students-move-out-of-dorms-by-tuesday-at-5-p-m-citing-public-health-guidance/ | title = Northeastern requests that students move out of dorms by Tuesday at 5:00&nbsp;p.m., citing public health guidance | website = [[Northeastern University]] | access-date = March 16, 2020}}</ref> [[Williams College]] announced it would end in-person classes on Friday, March 13 and move to remote learning beginning Monday, April 6.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.williams.edu/coronavirus/ | title = Coronavirus (COVID-19) | website = [[Williams College]] | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> [[Boston College]] moved all classes online, and all students were told to vacate their dorms by March 15.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bc.edu/content/bc-web/sites/updates/coronavirus.html | title = Coronavirus Updates | website = [[Boston College]] | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> All [[University of Massachusetts]] classes moved online until at least April 3.<ref name=\"Corrado\"/> Within a week, many colleges and state school districts announced closures ranging from weeks to months in duration.<ref name=\"Williams-Update\">{{cite web|url=https://www.masslive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/massachusetts-coronavirus-update-schools-closing-or-changing-schedules-for-monday-march-16.html|title=Massachusetts coronavirus update: Schools closing or changing schedules for Monday, March 16|last=Williams|first=Michelle|date=March 13, 2020|website=MassLive|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Williams-Colleges\">{{cite web|url=https://www.masslive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-and-massachusetts-updated-list-of-massachusetts-colleges-with-canceled-classes-plans-to-switch-to-online-instruction-march-13.html|title=Coronavirus and Massachusetts: Updated list of Massachusetts colleges with canceled classes, plans to switch to online instruction (March 13)|last=Williams|first=Michelle|date=March 14, 2020|publisher=MassLive}}</ref> \n\nWellesley and Framingham closed their public schools and libraries for two weeks on March 13.<ref>{{cite web | title = WPS Update 3/13/2020 | website = Wellesley Public Schools | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://wellesleyps.org/blog/2020/03/13/wps-update-3-13-2020/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Town of Wellesley COVID-19 Update 3/13/2020 | website = Wellesley Public Schools | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://wellesleyps.org/blog/2020/03/13/town-of-wellesley-covid-19-update-3-13-2020/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Framingham Library, Callahan Center, Loring Arena, and Public Schools to Close for a Minimum of Two Weeks Starting Friday, March 13 | website = Framingham, MA | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.framinghamma.gov/CivicAlerts.aspx?AID=2023 | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | title = Framingham Library, Callahan Center, Loring Arena, and Public Schools to Close for a Minimum of Two Weeks Starting Friday, March 13 | website = Framingham, MA | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.framinghamma.gov/DocumentCenter/View/37162/Press-Release---COVID-19-Update-031320204265 | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 13, Boston announced that its public schools would close for six weeks from Tuesday, March 17 through April 26.<ref>{{cite web | title = Boston Public Schools to close Tuesday, with plans to reopen April 27 | website = [[The Boston Globe]] | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/13/nation/mayor-walsh-address-coronavirus-outbreak-friday-evening/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, Boston Mayor Walsh announced that [[Boston Public Schools]] would be closed starting on March 17 until April 27.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/boston-mayor-marty-walsh-coronavirus-update/2090828/ | title = Boston Public Schools to Close for Over a Month Starting Tuesday Over Coronavirus | date = March 13, 2020 | website = NBC Boston}}</ref> On March 15, Governor Baker ordered all schools in Massachusetts closed for three weeks from March 17 through April 7.<ref name=\"Becker\"/> On March 25, he extended the closing through May 4.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baker: schools to open no sooner than May 4th |url=https://www.westernmassnews.com/news/baker-schools-to-open-no-sooner-than-may/article_dfa2979c-6ed0-11ea-8d2f-9f9402f5677e.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |publisher=www.westernmassnews.com |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, [[Harvard University]] declared that its 369th Commencement Exercises would be postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boston25news.com/news/coronavirus-live-blog-msp-warning-about-covid-19-thefts/WUF4Z3XGGVDVBES6E3WMOCJYRQ/|title=Coronavirus live blog: Confirmed cases jumps to 413, state not planning shelter-in-place order|website=WFXT|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Sports ===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nMost of the state's sports teams were affected. Several leagues began postponing or suspending their seasons starting March 12, and [[Major League Baseball]] canceled the remainder of spring training. On March 16, after the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] recommended restricting events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, the major league baseball season was postponed indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back | title = Opening of regular season to be pushed back | first = Mark | last = Feinsand | website = [[MLB.com]] | date = March 16, 2020 | access-date = March 16, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games | title = Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days | date = March 12, 2020 | website = ESPN.com | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[National Hockey League]] season was suspended indefinitely.<ref>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] NHL, March 12, 2020</ref> Boston Celtics player [[Marcus Smart]] announced on March 18 that he had tested positive for COVID-19, having been tested five days prior.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wcvb.com/article/boston-celtics-player-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-team-confirms/31792637|title=Celtics' Marcus Smart tests positive for coronavirus|date=March 20, 2020|website=WCVB|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe [[2020 Boston Marathon]], which was originally scheduled to take place on April 20, was postponed to September 14. This was the first postponement of the Boston Marathon since it was first held in 1897.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.espn.com/olympics/story/_/id/28897435/boston-marathon-postponed-sept-14-amid-coronavirus-concerns|title = Boston Marathon postponed until Sept. 14 amid coronavirus concerns|website = ESPN|date = March 13, 2020|accessdate = March 31, 2020}}</ref> Baker cautioned runners to refrain from running the route on Marathon Monday in April.\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] canceled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Massachusetts}}\n* [https://www.mass.gov/resource/information-on-the-outbreak-of-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19 Coronavirus information] from the [[Massachusetts Department of Public Health]]\n* {{cite web | title=COVID-19 Information and Resources | website=[[Massachusetts Department of Elementary and Secondary Education]] | url=http://www.doe.mass.edu/sfs/emergencyplan/covid19.html }}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:2020 in Massachusetts|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Health in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "GorillaWarfare", "label": "safe", "comment": "+ missing cite", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Massachusetts"}
{"title_page": "2016 Tokyo 10th district by-election", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2016 Tokyo 10th district by-election\n| country            = Japan\n| type               = by-election\n| seats_for_election = [[Tokyo 10th district]]\n| ongoing            = no\n| previous_election  = 2014 Japanese general election\n| previous_year      = 2014\n| next_election      = Next Japanese general election\n| next_year          = Next\n| election_date      = ''23 October 2016''\n| turnout            = 34.85\n| image1             = [[File:Masaru Wakasa IMG 5348 20130706.JPG|100x80px]]\n| nominee1           = [[Masaru Wakasa]]\n| party1             = Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)\n| popular_vote1      = 75,755\n| percentage1        = 60.26\n| image2             = \n| nominee2           = Yosuke Suzuki\n| party2             = Democratic Party (Japan, 2016)\n| popular_vote2      = 47,141\n| percentage2        = 37.50\n| image3             = \n| nominee3           = Toshimitsu Yoshii\n| party3             = Happiness Realization Party\n| popular_vote3      = 2,824\n| percentage3        = 2.25\n| map_image          =\n| map_size           =\n| map_caption        =\n| title              = Representative\n| before_election    = [[Yuriko Koike]]\n| before_party       = Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)\n| after_election     = [[Masaru Wakasa]]\n| after_party        = Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)\n}}\nA '''by-election''' for the [[Tokyo 10th district]] in the Japanese [[House of Representatives (Japan)|Japanese House of Representatives]] was held on 23 October 2016 to replace [[Yuriko Koike]], who vacated the seat to contest the [[2016 Tokyo gubernatorial election|Tokyo gubernatorial election]] in July 2016. Koike, a member of the [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic Party]] (LDP), had represented the district since the [[2012 Japanese general election|December 2012]] general election and also served a previous term from 2005-2009. The election was won by LDP candidate [[Masaru Wakasa]], an incumbent member for the [[Tokyo proportional representation block]] who had supported Koike during her gubernatorial campaign. A separate by-election for the [[2016 Fukuoka 6th district by-election|Fukuoka 6th district]] was held on the same day.<ref name=JT1>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2016/10/06/national/politics-diplomacy/ldp-koike-mend-fences-ahead-election-former-seat/ |title=LDP, Koike mend fences ahead of by-election for her former seat |work=Japan Times |date=6 October 2016 |access-date=11 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nYuriko Koike, a [[Kansai]] native who had represented various Kansai districts in the House of Representatives since 1993, was parachuted into the Tokyo 10th district by LDP Prime Minister [[Junichiro Koizumi]] for the [[2005 Japanese general election|2005 general election]] following the defection of {{Interlanguage link multi|Koki Kobayashi|ja|3=\u5c0f\u6797\u8208\u8d77}}, who had held the seat for the LDP since its creation in 1996. Koike defeated Kobayashi in the 2005 election but lost to [[Democratic Party (Japan, 1998)|Democratic Party of Japan]] (DPJ) candidate {{Interlanguage link multi|Takako Ebata|ja|3=\u6c5f\u7aef\u8cb4\u5b50}} in 2009. Koike regained the seat from Ebata at the 2012 election and retained it at the 2014 general election.\n\nTokyo governor [[Yoichi Masuzoe]] resigned in June 2016 due to various problems with his use of public funds. On 29 June Koike held a press conference and stated her intention to contest the gubernatorial election to replace Masuzoe that was scheduled for 31 July.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jiji.com/jc/p?id=20160629113638-0021759848 |title=\u5c0f\u6c60\u5143\u9632\u885b\u76f8\u304c\u51fa\u99ac\u8868\u660e\uff1d\u90fd\u77e5\u4e8b\u9078 |trans-title=Former Defence Minister Koike intends to contest Tokyo gubernatorial election |date=29 June 2016 |language=Japanese |work=Jiji |access-date=13 October 2016}}</ref> On 5 July Koike met with [[Nobuteru Ishihara]], the head of the LDP's Tokyo branch, to formally request the LDP's endorsement. However, with the branch planning to endorse former [[Iwate Prefecture]] governor [[Hiroya Masuda]], Ishihara's response to Koike was that the branch would make a decision after the national [[2016 Japanese House of Councillors election|House of Councillors election]] on 10 July.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/election/local/20160705-OYT1T50054.html |title=\u77f3\u539f\u6c0f\u3001\u4f1a\u8ac7\u3067\u5c0f\u6c60\u6c0f\u306b\u300c\u53c2\u9662\u9078\u5f8c\u306b\u7d50\u8ad6\u51fa\u3059\u300d |trans-title=Ishihara meets with Koike \"Decision after the House of Councillors election\" |work=Yomiuri Shimbun |language=Japanese |date=5 July 2016 |access-date=13 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816140949/http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/election/local/20160705-OYT1T50054.html |archive-date=16 August 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Candidates ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=4 | Candidates<ref name=candidates>{{cite web|url=http://www.senkyo.metro.tokyo.jp/uploads/h28syuugiinhosen_kouhosha.pdf |title=\u5e73\u621028\u5e7410\u670823\u65e5\u57f7\u884c\u3000\u8846\u8b70\u9662\u8b70\u54e1\u88dc\u6b20\u9078\u6319\uff08\u6771\u4eac\u90fd\u7b2c10\u533a\uff09\u3000\u7acb\u5019\u88dc\u8005\u4e00\u89a7 |trans-title=23 October 2016 Tokyo 10th District By-Election List of Candidates |language=Japanese |publisher=Tokyo Metropolitan Electoral Commission |access-date=12 October 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Democratic Party (Japan, 2016)/meta/color}}\"|&nbsp;\n| [[Democratic Party (Japan, 2016)|Democratic]]\n| Yosuke Suzuki\n| Supported by the [[Japanese Communist Party|Communist]], [[Liberal Party (Japan, 2016)|Liberal]] and [[Social Democratic Party (Japan)|Social Democratic]] parties.<ref name=summary2>{{cite web|url=http://www.sankei.com/politics/news/161023/plt1610230014-n2.html |title=\u3010\u8846\u9662\u30c0\u30d6\u30eb\u88dc\u9078\u3011\u6771\u4eac\uff11\uff10\u533a\u306f\u5c0f\u6c60\u767e\u5408\u5b50\u6c0f\u652f\u63f4\u306e\u81ea\u6c11\u30fb\u82e5\u72ed\u52dd\u6c0f\u304c\u52dd\u5229\u3000\u798f\u5ca1\uff16\u533a\u306f\u9ce9\u5c71\u90a6\u592b\u6c0f\u306e\u6b21\u7537\u304c\u5206\u88c2\u9078\u6319\u3092\u5236\u3059 |trans-title=(House of Reps. Double By-Election) LDP's Masaru Wakasa supported by Yuriko Koike wins Tokyo 10th, Kunio Hatoyama's second son victorious in divisive Fukuoka 6th election (Page 2) |work=Sankei Shimbun |language=Japanese |date=23 October 2016 |access-date=25 October 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)/meta/color}}\"|&nbsp;\n| [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic]]\n| [[Masaru Wakasa]]\n| Incumbent representative for the [[Tokyo proportional representation block]]. Received official endorsement from [[Komeito]].<ref name=summary1>{{cite web|url=http://www.sankei.com/politics/news/161023/plt1610230014-n1.html |title=\u3010\u8846\u9662\u30c0\u30d6\u30eb\u88dc\u9078\u3011\u6771\u4eac\uff11\uff10\u533a\u306f\u5c0f\u6c60\u767e\u5408\u5b50\u6c0f\u652f\u63f4\u306e\u81ea\u6c11\u30fb\u82e5\u72ed\u52dd\u6c0f\u304c\u52dd\u5229\u3000\u798f\u5ca1\uff16\u533a\u306f\u9ce9\u5c71\u90a6\u592b\u6c0f\u306e\u6b21\u7537\u304c\u5206\u88c2\u9078\u6319\u3092\u5236\u3059 |trans-title=(House of Reps. Double By-Election) LDP's Masaru Wakasa supported by Yuriko Koike wins Tokyo 10th, Kunio Hatoyama's second son victorious in divisive Fukuoka 6th election (Page 1) |work=Sankei Shimbun |language=Japanese |date=23 October 2016 |access-date=25 October 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Happiness Realization Party/meta/color}}\"|&nbsp;\n| [[Happiness Realization Party|Happiness Realization]]\n| Toshimitsu Yoshii\n| Listed as an independent in official documents<ref name=candidates/>\n|-\n|}\n<!--\n== Campaign ==\n{{empty section|date=June 2016}}\n-->\n\n== Results ==\n{{Election box begin|title=Tokyo 10th district by-election, 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.senkyo.metro.tokyo.jp/h28syuugiinhosensokuhou/kaihyo.pdf|title=\u8846\u8b70\u9662\uff08\u5c0f\u9078\u6319\u533a\u9078\u51fa\uff09\u8b70\u54e1\u88dc\u6b20\u9078\u6319\u3000\u5019\u88dc\u8005\u5225\u5f97\u7968\u6570\uff08\u5168\u5019\u88dc\uff09|publisher=Tokyo Metropolitan Electoral Commission|access-date=25 October 2016|language=Japanese|trans-title=House of Representatives (Individual Districts) By-Election Results by Candidate (All Candidates)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025111812/http://www.senkyo.metro.tokyo.jp/h28syuugiinhosensokuhou/kaihyo.pdf|archive-date=25 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.senkyo.metro.tokyo.jp/h28syuugiinhosensokuhou/touhyou20.pdf|title=\u8846\u8b70\u9662\uff08\u5c0f\u9078\u6319\u533a\u9078\u51fa\uff09\u8b70\u54e1\u88dc\u6b20\u9078\u6319\u3000\u6295\u7968\u7d50\u679c\u3000\uff08\u56fd\u5185\uff0b\u5728\u5916\uff09|publisher=Tokyo Metropolitan Electoral Commission|access-date=25 October 2016|language=Japanese|trans-title=House of Representatives (Individual Districts) By-Election Turnout (Inside and Outside Japan)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025111210/http://www.senkyo.metro.tokyo.jp/h28syuugiinhosensokuhou/touhyou20.pdf|archive-date=25 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>}}\n {{Election box candidate with party link|\n   |party      = Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)\n   |candidate  = '''[[Masaru Wakasa]]''' <br /><small>(endorsed by [[Komeito]])</small>\n   |votes      = 75,755\n   |percentage = 60.26\n   |change     = \n }}\n {{Election box candidate with party link|\n   |party      = Democratic Party (Japan, 2016)\n   |candidate  = Yosuke Suzuki\n   |votes      = 47,141\n   |percentage = 37.50\n   |change     = \n }}\n {{Election box candidate with party link|\n   |party      = Happiness Realization Party\n   |candidate  = Toshimitsu Yoshii\n   |votes      = 2,824\n   |percentage = 2.25\n   |change     = \n }}\n  {{Election box turnout|\n   |votes      = 127,965\n   |percentage = 34.85\n   |change     = -18.71\n }}\n  {{Election box end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2016 elections in Japan]]\n[[Category:By-elections in Japan|2016]]\n[[Category:October 2016 events in Japan]]\n[[Category:2016 in Tokyo]]\n\n[[ja:2016\u5e74\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u88dc\u6b20\u9078\u6319#\u8846\u8b70\u9662\u6771\u4eac\u90fd\u7b2c10\u533a]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2016 Tokyo 10th district by-election\n| country            = Japan\n| type               = by-election\n| seats_for_election = [[Tokyo 10th district]]\n| ongoing            = no\n| previous_election  = 2014 Japanese general election\n| previous_year      = 2014\n| next_election      = Next Japanese general election\n| next_year          = Next\n| election_date      = ''23 October 2016''\n| turnout            = 34.85\n| image1             = [[File:Masaru Wakasa IMG 5348 20130706.JPG|100x80px]]\n| nominee1           = [[Masaru Wakasa]]\n| party1             = Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)\n| popular_vote1      = 75,755\n| percentage1        = 60.26\n| image2             = \n| nominee2           = Yosuke Suzuki\n| party2             = Democratic Party (Japan, 2016)\n| popular_vote2      = 47,141\n| percentage2        = 37.50\n| image3             = \n| nominee3           = Toshimitsu Yoshii\n| party3             = Happiness Realization Party\n| popular_vote3      = 2,824\n| percentage3        = 2.25\n| map_image          =\n| map_size           =\n| map_caption        =\n| title              = Representative\n| before_election    = [[Yuriko Koike]]\n| before_party       = Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)\n| after_election     = [[Masaru Wakasa]]\n| after_party        = Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)\n}}\nA '''by-election''' for the [[Tokyo 10th district]] in the Japanese [[House of Representatives (Japan)|Japanese House of Representatives]] was held on 23 October 2016 to replace [[Yuriko Koike]], who vacated the seat to contest the [[2016 Tokyo gubernatorial election|Tokyo gubernatorial election]] in July 2016. Koike, a member of the [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic Party]] (LDP), had represented the district since the [[2012 Japanese general election|December 2012]] general election and also served a previous term from 2005-2009. The election was won by LDP candidate [[Masaru Wakasa]], an incumbent member for the [[Tokyo proportional representation block]] who had supported Koike during her gubernatorial campaign. A separate by-election for the [[2016 Fukuoka 6th district by-election|Fukuoka 6th district]] was held on the same day.<ref name=JT1>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2016/10/06/national/politics-diplomacy/ldp-koike-mend-fences-ahead-election-former-seat/ |title=LDP, Koike mend fences ahead of by-election for her former seat |work=Japan Times |date=6 October 2016 |access-date=11 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nYuriko Koike, a [[Kansai]] native who had represented various Kansai districts in the House of Representatives since 1993, was parachuted into the Tokyo 10th district by LDP Prime Minister [[Junichiro Koizumi]] for the [[2005 Japanese general election|2005 general election]] following the defection of {{Interlanguage link multi|Koki Kobayashi|ja|3=\u5c0f\u6797\u8208\u8d77}}, who had held the seat for the LDP since its creation in 1996. Koike defeated Kobayashi in the 2005 election but lost to [[Democratic Party (Japan, 1998)|Democratic Party of Japan]] (DPJ) candidate {{Interlanguage link multi|Takako Ebata|ja|3=\u6c5f\u7aef\u8cb4\u5b50}} in 2009. Koike regained the seat from Ebata at the 2012 election and retained it at the 2014 general election.\n\nTokyo governor [[Yoichi Masuzoe]] resigned in June 2016 due to various problems with his use of public funds. On 29 June Koike held a press conference and stated her intention to contest the gubernatorial election to replace Masuzoe that was scheduled for 31 July.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jiji.com/jc/p?id=20160629113638-0021759848 |title=\u5c0f\u6c60\u5143\u9632\u885b\u76f8\u304c\u51fa\u99ac\u8868\u660e\uff1d\u90fd\u77e5\u4e8b\u9078 |trans-title=Former Defence Minister Koike intends to contest Tokyo gubernatorial election |date=29 June 2016 |language=Japanese |work=Jiji |access-date=13 October 2016}}</ref> On 5 July Koike met with [[Nobuteru Ishihara]], the head of the LDP's Tokyo branch, to formally request the LDP's endorsement. However, with the branch planning to endorse former [[Iwate Prefecture]] governor [[Hiroya Masuda]], Ishihara's response to Koike was that the branch would make a decision after the national [[2016 Japanese House of Councillors election|House of Councillors election]] on 10 July.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/election/local/20160705-OYT1T50054.html |title=\u77f3\u539f\u6c0f\u3001\u4f1a\u8ac7\u3067\u5c0f\u6c60\u6c0f\u306b\u300c\u53c2\u9662\u9078\u5f8c\u306b\u7d50\u8ad6\u51fa\u3059\u300d |trans-title=Ishihara meets with Koike \"Decision after the House of Councillors election\" |work=Yomiuri Shimbun |language=Japanese |date=5 July 2016 |access-date=13 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816140949/http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/election/local/20160705-OYT1T50054.html |archive-date=16 August 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Candidates ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=4 | Candidates<ref name=candidates>{{cite web|url=http://www.senkyo.metro.tokyo.jp/uploads/h28syuugiinhosen_kouhosha.pdf |title=\u5e73\u621028\u5e7410\u670823\u65e5\u57f7\u884c\u3000\u8846\u8b70\u9662\u8b70\u54e1\u88dc\u6b20\u9078\u6319\uff08\u6771\u4eac\u90fd\u7b2c10\u533a\uff09\u3000\u7acb\u5019\u88dc\u8005\u4e00\u89a7 |trans-title=23 October 2016 Tokyo 10th District By-Election List of Candidates |language=Japanese |publisher=Tokyo Metropolitan Electoral Commission |access-date=12 October 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\